# {{ machine_class_name(model) }}

This directory contains the generated C99 / C++98-compatible `c_poll` runtime
for the DSL root state `{{ model.root_state.name }}`.

The generated `machine.h` and `machine.c` are intended to stay close to a
4-space `clang-format` style so formatter-driven integration should converge
cleanly.

## Generated Files

- `machine.h`: public runtime header
- `machine.c`: generated runtime implementation
- `README.md`: English usage guide for this generated machine
- `README_zh.md`: Chinese usage guide for this generated machine

## Runtime Overview

This generated runtime is a self-contained C99 / C++98+ state-machine engine
specialized for the concrete DSL model. It follows the `c_poll` event-input
contract:

- `machine.h` is the integration surface for application code
- `machine.c` contains generated execution logic and should usually be treated
  as a black-box implementation detail
- abstract lifecycle hooks are registered through
  `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}Hooks`
- event input is provided through `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}EventChecks`
  instead of per-cycle event-id arrays
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_cycle(&machine)` executes one cycle using
  the installed event-check table
- if the model declares events, `cycle()` fails fast until a complete event-
  check table has been mounted with
  `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_set_event_checks(...)`
- hot start restores a full variable snapshot into a generated state id and
  preserves any already-installed hook and event-check tables
- failed speculative transitions still roll back to the previous committed
  machine state
- generated identifiers are normalized for both C and C++, including escaping
  keyword collisions such as `class` or `template`

The public header exposes some runtime-layout structs for ABI simplicity, but
runtime-owned internals should not be modified directly unless the field is
explicitly documented for external use.

## Event-Check Contract

`c_poll` does not accept per-cycle external event-id arrays. Instead, each DSL
event is mapped to one generated `check_xxx` field inside
`{{ machine_class_name(model) }}EventChecks`.

When the runtime needs to decide whether a transition guarded by an event may
fire in the current cycle, it calls the corresponding event-check function:

- return non-zero: the event is considered active or triggered for the current
  cycle, so the transition may continue to guard evaluation
- return `0`: the event is considered inactive or not triggered for the current
  cycle, so the transition must not fire through that event path

The generated runtime caches the first observation of each event inside one
cycle. That means a single event-check function should behave like a read-only
probe for "is this event active now?" rather than a destructive consume/ack
operation.

## Build

Compile the generated runtime directly with a C99 compiler:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -c machine.c -o machine.o
```

For optimized production builds:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -O3 -DNDEBUG -c machine.c -o machine.o
```

On POSIX-like platforms, a shared-library build can look like this:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -shared -fPIC machine.c -lm -o libmachine.so
```

On Windows, use the equivalent DLL flags for your compiler toolchain and
define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_BUILD_SHARED` when exporting symbols.

Compile checking with a C++ compiler is also supported and recommended when
your integration layer is C++:

```bash
g++ -x c++ -std=c++98 -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic-errors -c machine.c -o machine.o
g++ -x c++ -std=c++17 -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic-errors -c machine.c -o machine.o
```

### Linkage and Visibility

- `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_API` is the generated symbol-visibility macro
  used by all public functions.
- Define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_BUILD_SHARED` when building the
  generated runtime itself as a Windows DLL.
- Define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_USE_SHARED` when consuming that DLL
  from external code on Windows.
- `machine.h` wraps only the public API declarations in `extern "C"` when
  included from C++.
- Public layout structs, hook typedefs, and event-check typedefs stay usable
  from both C and C++.
- In generated integer fields, `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}Int` is the
  public signed 64-bit type alias chosen to stay valid in both C99 and C++98+.

