- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_create()` /
  `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_destroy()`:
  use these if you want heap allocation managed by the generated runtime.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_init()`:
  use this for stack-allocated machines or to reset an existing machine. After
  reset, reinstall hooks and event checks as needed.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_hot_start()`:
  `initial_vars` must describe a complete persistent-state snapshot compatible
  with `initial_state_id`. Hot start preserves already-installed hook and
  event-check tables.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_set_event_checks()`:
  for eventful machines, provide a complete generated table. Partial tables are
  rejected and leave the machine non-runnable for `cycle()`.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_cycle()`:
  executes one cycle using the currently installed event-check table. If the
  table is missing or incomplete, the call returns
  `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_FAILURE` and `last_error` explains why.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_vars()`:
  returns a read-only pointer; if you need a mutable external snapshot, copy the
  struct value out first.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_last_error()`:
  useful after any API call that returned `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_FAILURE`.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_dsl_source()`:
  useful for diagnostics, traceability, or embedding the original model text in
